entry.title: [iOS] Pass Safety Check module type as argument when disabling module.
entry.content:
This change fixes a crash when disabling the Safety Check module.



Instead of calculating the current Safety Check module type on-the-fly

before disabling the module, this change passes the module type at the

time the disable request is made.



This ensures any async changes made to _safetyCheckState don't affect

the module type passed into `-indexForMagicStackModule:`, resulting in a

crash.



Fixed: 1485050

entry.title: Add output buffer bypass to WebAudio
entry.content:
Currently audio_destination will pull audio data from the previous

callback before generating new audio data and pushing it to the

FIFO. This results in one callback size of of additional latency.



This change does the following, behind a command-line switch:

- Pull audio data immediately after it is generated

- Do not prime the output FIFO

- Do not use the adaptive growth mechanism of the output FIFO



The output FIFO is still necessary because the requested frames

may not be a multiple of the render quantum size.



With this feature enabled, instead of underruns in the FIFO we will

get messages like the following from the audio backend if there are

underruns:



WARNING:sync_reader.cc(255)] SyncReader::Read timed out,

audio glitch count=10



This patch requires waiting on the AudioWorklet runner thread.

Ideally, we would run the AudioWorklet on the main audio thread

instead, but I haven't figured out how to do that yet.



Latency test results (Linux using PulseAudio backend):



Using command:

out/Default/chrome --audio-buffer-size=128 --disable-features=WebAudioBypassOutputBuffering https://padenot.github.io/roundtrip-latency-tester/



Result:

- AudioContext sample-rate: : 48000

- Measured roundtrip: 93.35416666666667ms

- Computed output latency: 22ms



Using command:

out/Default/chrome --audio-buffer-size=128 --enable-features=WebAudioBypassOutputBuffering https://padenot.github.io/roundtrip-latency-tester/



Result:

- AudioContext sample-rate: : 48000

- Measured roundtrip: 72.02083333333334ms

- Computed output latency: 22ms



(note that 128 samples at 48000 Hz is about 2.67 ms)

entry.title: Move frame drop UMAs from Browser to Renderer process.
entry.content:
This CL moves logging/UMA about frame drops from VideoCaptureController

(Browser process) to the MediaStreamVideoTrack (Renderer process).

- This reduces PostTasks, IPC messages and the number of different

frame drop callbacks that exist spread out in the code.

- A follow-up CL[1] will delete the frame drop plumbing. This means

that the only frame drop events will flow in one direction

(Capturer -> Browser -> Renderer) with no signals back again.



In short, the code in VideoCaptureController is cut-and-paste to

MediaStreamVideoTrack::FrameDeliverer on the video task runner.



"Media.VideoCapture" is renamed to "Media.VideoCapture.Track" to

reflect that collection now happens per-track instead of per-source.



The FrameDeliverer's OnFrameDroppedOnVideoTaskRunner() now handles all

frame drops, regardless if they happened in the capturer or in the

renderer. Instead of notifying the source which resulted in IPC to the

Browser process' VideoCaptureController, the logging and UMA happens in

the FrameDeliverer's LogFrameDroppedOnVideoTaskRunner(). The only IPC

involves is EmitLogMessage() which gets suppressed after 3 logs.



VideoTrackAdapter (the layer between the source and the track which

decides frame rate etc) can also be simplified to having a single

OnFrameDropped that is just forwarded to its callbacks, instead of

mixing callbacks to track and callback to source separately.



[1] https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4891622

entry.title: Revert "apple: Disable global isel"
entry.content:
This reverts commit b48399969320056a74680f5db3850e7f7cb8817d.



Reason for revert: Global ISel is disabled by default

upstream again. It got enabled on Nov 7 2022 in

https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/commit/f64802e8d3e9d and

then reverted again on Nov 11 2022 in

https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/commit/28e07984c342

and hasn't been reenabled since.



This does have the effect of re-enabling the pass on

arm64 in -O0 builds, where the pass is enabled by default.

It has no effect in release builds.



I tried reverting this in

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4089467

already, but back there I reverted the change on the branch, not

on trunk.



Original change's description:

> apple: Disable global isel

>

> Global ISel was enabled for a bit by default in upstream LLVM (since

> reverted, but our currently rolled-in clang doesn't have the revert yet).

>

> In LTO builds, Global ISel very visibly breaks layout, so turn it off.

>

> (If you do a local LTO build before syncing, and then sync in this

> change, you might need to `gn clean` your build dir for this change to have an effect.)

entry.title: Set has_started_first_navigation_ correctly in ExtensionFrameHelper
entry.content:
ExtensionFrameHelper::ReadyToCommitNavigation() watches for the first

navigation in a new Chrome Apps window to block the parsing of the new

document, so that the create() function's callback is called before

the document is loaded.



However, it can currently mistakenly think that a non-first

navigation that uses a new RenderFrame and a new ExtensionFrameHelper

is actually a first navigation, because it tracks that information

with has_started_first_navigation_, which is false on new

ExtensionFrameHelpers. New RenderFrames will be created on cross-site

navigations, or every cross-document navigation if RenderDocument is

enabled.



This CL fixes this by setting has_started_first_navigation_ to true

if it sees that the ExtensionFrameHelper is created for a frame that

had navigated before (loaded a non-initial empty document).



See also: https://groups.google.com/a/google.com/g/chrome-security-architecture/c/vcWW1xOdUjw/m/BU6e5OE7AwAJ
